Goal of the thread: Treat yourself to something nice, be it a meal, a hot bath, or something else you'd enjoy doing.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

If any resource below is unhelpful, please let me know. I can't assert their quality on my own.

Anon, you may not realize it, but these threads are for people *exactly* like you. I am here for you people because I know how difficult life is. And I want to help you with the small steps. The big steps you will manage no problem on your own when you are ready.
> i have to jump through all these mental hoops to convince myself to do the things i want to do, things that normal people don't even think twice about.
that is normal with depression in the way of things. It is in the nature of it to feel that way. You are not broken. You are living through something difficult and challenging. Healing means making simple things easier again. You only see the things you want to do being simple, and focus on how normal people would "just do it". But that is not quite right. Everything requires mental energy, and what you are going through deprives you a great deal of it. A "normal person" would struggle in your stead, too.
>i want to use the new year as an excuse to start exercising and dieting but if i fail i'll get even more depressed.
The important thing is to remember to start small and well defined. You will sometimes get discouraged, some things will fail. It's all in the OP. But it is part of the healing process and you do not have to be alone. This thread has a tiny handful of resources, I hope they will be useful to you. But this thread also has people. You can always come back. Talk about your roadblocks. Find a little bit of support.

posts.com:
>>28978129
I understand the need to talk to people who share your struggle, and despite how bad tttt can be at times, I have met many absolutely wonderful people here and on 4chan in general. But you should open up more about this in front of your bf, I know many partners exhaust easily from deep feelings talks, and not every relationship works like the ones my limited experiences are drawn from, but please, remember what I said in the OP: shame is your greatest enemy in getting better. It is hard to let go of it, but feelings aren't rational. You are not somehow at fault for feeling this way, you can only hope to resolve it. You have come so, so far already. Instead of feeling shame for shaking one of the few remaining things weighing you down, reflect on how many successes you have already under your belt. Relative to how far you have come, this is just another small thing for you to eventually overcome. There is no switch in your head that will make you adapt this mindset over night, but I hope my words help you finding your own way into it, but by bit.

sounds kinda gay to me but this is a pretty widespread view, i think mostly because the only times you hear about postmodernism are in contexts where it's being derided, whereas so-called 'postmodernists' will rarely address it at all except by referring to the historical period of postmodernity
generally i would deny the existence of any unified philosophical movement or school that could be called 'postmodernism'. but then, that's the most postmodernist thing one could possibly say
when you stop conceiving of 'postmodernism' as a rabidly critical heresy of the enlightenment, propped up by esoteric academics, and start conceiving it as the condition of postmodernity as a historical period, propped up by social system-logics which reinforce particular behaviours and unconscious ideological axioms, i think there's much more of a critique to be made. this is a significant part of why i think zizek's critique of deleuze and guattari is a good one, though instead of making it the basis for a rejection of their work i think it ought to be used as the basis for an immanent critique of postmodernity through the lens of deleuzoguattarian philosophy
